	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Pressure for increased EU aid in response to dairy crisis</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 November 2009
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Following a milk delivery strike by over 60,000 EU dairy farmers in response to the 25% decline in milk prices, political pressure for further EC action increased. This gave rise to the convening of an emergency Agriculture Council meeting which took place on 5 October. At this meeting, Agriculture Commissioner Fischer Boel reiterated the existing EC position and announced the launch of a number of new initiatives. Current EU support measures for the dairy sector include:</p>
<ul>

<li>direct-aid payments of €5 billion per annum to EU dairy farmers;</li>

<li>the allocation of an addition €600 million to market-support instruments in response to the dairy crisis;</li>

<li>the expansion of the school milk scheme;</li>

<li>the financing of a new round of dairy-product promotion programmes;</li>

<li>the availability of rural development financing and the consumption impact of the Economic Recovery programme.</li>

</ul>
<p>The Commissioner further indicated that member states would be allowed to offer farmers up to €15,000 in state aid under the Temporary Crisis Framework measures, while procedures for securing EC support would be streamlined and rules on certain milk-quota buy-out schemes would be temporarily changed to facilitate production restructuring.</p><p>Commissioner Fischer Boel also announced the launch of a high-level group to look at the future of the dairy sector. This high-level group is chaired by the Commission’s director-general for agriculture and rural development and is composed of member state representatives. Issues to be addressed by the high-level group include:</p>
<ul>

<li>the legal framework for contractual relations between milk farmers and the dairy industry;</li>

<li>the scope for strengthening the bargaining power of milk producers within these commercial relationships;</li>

<li>the appropriateness of existing market-support instruments;</li>

<li>the possible role of an EU dairy futures market;</li>

<li>improved transparency and information to consumers on quality, health and labelling issues;</li>

<li>innovation and research to enhance dairy-sector competitiveness.</li>

</ul>
<p>The first meeting of the high-level milk group was held within one week of the announcement of its launch, with the focus being on ‘contractual relations and bargaining power in the dairy sector’. Issues discussed included: the need for formalised contracts between dairy farmers and dairy processors, what such contracts should cover, and the penalties for breach of contract and how the bargaining position of dairy farmers can be strengthened. The next meeting of the group is scheduled to take place on 10 November, after which hearings will be held to receive representations, opinions and analysis from producers, processors, national competition authorities, academics, consumers and distributors. Further meetings will then take place on 8 December and in January 2010, when experiences in third countries will be reviewed. A conference on the issues discussed is then scheduled to be held in March 2010. </p><p>The EC argues that the measures already adopted in response to the crisis have begun to bear fruit. Indeed, EU ministers acknowledged at their special meeting that ‘the dairy sector is beginning to show signs of recovery’: ‘on the spot markets, between July and September the raw milk price rose by 12% in Italy, 19% in Northern Ireland and 50% in the Netherlands. Prices are also improving visibly for butter and skimmed-milk powder’. However the situation varies considerably across EU regions. The milk delivery boycott initiated by EU farmers also caused the market to react, with an increase in spot prices for milk being triggered.</p><p>While there appears to be widespread support among EU member states for a regulated framework for the dairy sector, the commitment to abolishing national production quotas remains fixed. Indeed, in the 2008-09 quota year, total EU milk production was 4.2% below quota (some 5.38 million tonnes below the overall quota, despite the introduction of the 2.4% increase in the overall quota). Against this background, Commissioner Fischer Boel has argued that ‘it is clear that the low farm-gate prices over the past few months have nothing to do with the gradual phase-out of the quota system’.</p><p>EU farmers expressed disappointment at the outcome of the special ministerial meeting on the dairy crisis and looked for further EC measures from the 19 October EU Agriculture Council meeting. Press reports indicate that an additional €280 million in support to dairy farmers is to be made available (pending a final decision by the Council of Finance Ministers) to allow for the implementation of measures under Article 168 of the Single CMO, the so-called disturbance clause. This provision has now been officially extended to include the dairy sector, and the move has been welcomed by dairy farmers’ leaders, although it remains unclear what specific measures will be implemented under this ‘disturbance clause’.</p>
		
		
